<h2>Closing</h2>

<p>None of this is about lowering the bar. The students in this course — every one of them, multilingual or not — are doing the same intellectual work: reading scientific source material critically, building argued positions from evidence, defending those positions in front of an audience, and reflecting on their own thinking and tool use.</p>

<p>What EAL access work does is keep the language load from masking the thinking. When you score a student's Position Paper at a 7–8 on K/U and a 5–6 on Communication, you are saying: this student's understanding of water-rights stakeholder dynamics is excellent, and their English prose is still developing. Both statements are true. Both belong in the gradebook. Neither erases the other.</p>

<p>Use this guide alongside the <a href="/foundations/eal/vocabulary/">Master Vocabulary Reference</a> and the per-unit Pre-Teach Handouts (linked from the <a href="/foundations/eal/">EAL hub</a>). The three documents are a set; each one assumes the other two.</p>

